  "prompt": "How do you round to one decimal place?",
  "response": "Here's how to round a number to one decimal place (also known as rounding to the nearest tenth):\n\n**1. Identify the Target Decimal Place:**\n\n   * The one decimal place is the digit immediately to the right of the decimal point. For example, in the number 3.14159, the target decimal place is '1'.\n\n**2. Look at the Digit to the Right (the \"Decider\"):**\n\n   * Look at the digit immediately to the *right* of your target decimal place. This is the digit that will determine whether you round up or down.  In 3.14159, the \"decider\" is '4'.\n\n**3. Rounding Rules:**\n\n   * **If the \"decider\" is 5 or greater (5, 6, 7, 8, 9):**  Round the target decimal place *up* by one. This means adding 1 to the digit in the target decimal place.\n   * **If the \"decider\" is less than 5 (0, 1, 2, 3, 4):** Keep the target decimal place the same.  You just drop all the digits to the right of the target.\n\n**Examples:**\n\n*   **3.14159:** The target decimal place is '1'. The decider is '4'. Since 4 is less than 5, the '1' stays the same.  Rounded to one decimal place, this is **3.1**\n\n*   **12.768:** The target decimal place is '7'. The decider is '6'. Since 6 is 5 or greater, we round the '7' *up* to '8'. Rounded to one decimal place, this is **12.8**\n\n*   **0.982:** The target decimal place is '9'. The decider is '8'. Since 8 is 5 or greater, we round the '9' *up*.  Rounding 9 up makes it 10.  So the '9' becomes a '0' and we carry-over the '1' to the whole number part, turning the '0' into a '1'. Rounded to one decimal place, this is **1.0** (Important: Don't forget the `.0` to show you rounded to one decimal place).\n\n*   **5.03:** The target decimal place is '0'. The decider is '3'. Since 3 is less than 5, the '0' stays the same. Rounded to one decimal place, this is **5.0**\n\n**In Summary:**\n\n1.  Identify the tenths place.\n2.  Look at the hundredths place.\n3.  5 or more, round the tenths place up. Less than 5, leave the tenths place as it is.\n4.  Remove all digits to the right of the tenths place.\n",
